16
00:01:56,310 --> 00:02:01,280
<i>After banishing all music from
her life she found a way...</i>

17
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:02,900
<i>to provide for her daughter.</i>

18
00:02:06,720 --> 00:02:10,190
<i>She rolled up her sleeves
and she learned to make shoes.</i>

19
00:02:10,190 --> 00:02:12,470
(HAMMERING)

20
00:02:15,360 --> 00:02:17,630
<i>She could have made candy,</i>

21
00:02:17,630 --> 00:02:20,730
<i>or fireworks,
or sparkly underwear...</i>

22
00:02:20,730 --> 00:02:26,050
<i>for wrestlers,
but no, she chose shoes.</i>

23
00:02:28,610 --> 00:02:30,920
<i>Then she taught her daughter
to make shoes.</i>

24
00:02:32,310 --> 00:02:34,890
<i>And later,
she taught her son-in-law.</i>

25
00:02:35,880 --> 00:02:37,880
<i>Then her grandkids
got roped in.</i>

26
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:39,520
(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

27
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:42,540
<i>As her family grew,
so did the business.</i>

28
00:02:43,890 --> 00:02:46,810
<i>Music had torn
her family apart.</i>

29
00:02:47,590 --> 00:02:49,940
<i>But shoes held
them all together.</i>

30
00:02:51,500 --> 00:02:53,260
<i>You see, that woman was</i>

31
00:02:53,270 --> 00:02:55,810
<i>my great-great-grandmother,</i>
Mama <i>Imelda.</i>

32
00:02:56,800 --> 00:02:59,640
<i>She died
way before I was born.</i>

33
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:01,810
<i>But my family
still tells her story</i>

34
00:03:01,810 --> 00:03:04,370
<i>every year
on</i> Dia de los Muertos...

35
00:03:04,380 --> 00:03:05,880
<i>the Day of the Dead.</i>

36
00:03:05,880 --> 00:03:07,780
<i>And her little girl,</i>

37
00:03:07,780 --> 00:03:10,230
